  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Ellis Gray Loring thanks Caroline Weston for her &quot;efficient exertions on Martin&apos;s account&quot; and accepts &quot;with the greatest satisfaction the opportunity of placing him with the Hortons.&quot; If the Hortons are not satisfied with him, &quot;he must go a-whaling,&quot; but Ellis G. Loring is &quot;glad to have a trial on shore.&quot; Ellis G. Loring sends a check for ten dollars for the boy&apos;s immediate needs.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">In the postscript, Ellis G. Loring states that he wishes the boy, Martin, decently clad. Caroline is to pay someone to attend to this and Ellis G. Loring will pay all expenses.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">For other letters by Ellis Gray Loring to Caroline Weston in which the boy named Martin, who is a former slave, is discussed, see Call No. Ms.A.9.2 v.22, p.17, letter dated Feb. 1, 1846, and Ms.A.9.2 v.22, p.9, letter dated Jan. 18, 1846.</subfield>
  </datafield>
